{"title_page": "Sollega", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{third-party|date=August 2017}}{{notability|1=Companies|date=August 2017}}}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Sollega\n| logo             = Sollega logo w tag 2013 RM.png\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2009}}\n| location_city    = [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| key_people       = Elie Rothschild, CEO<br />Lee Rothschild, Director of Engineering <br />Juan Carlos Chavez, Solar PV System Designer <br /> Bryan Weinberg, Account Manager \n| industry         = Solar Racking\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.sollega.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Sollega''' is a US based solar racking company that provides solutions for flat mount and ground mount solar arrays for commercial and industrial use. Sollega operates out of The [[Mission District]] in San Francisco, California.\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded in 2009 by Elie Rothschild, John Humphrey, and George Schnackenberg III. Sollega proposed a cheaper alternative to the conventional metal mounting systems. The company produced its first racking system Instarack 15\u00b0 followed by the Instarack 10\u00b0. These were replaced with the updated Fastrack 5\u00b0 in 2012. In 2014 this was replaced by the current system, the Fastrack 510.\n\n==Major Installations==\n[[File:OCC2.jpg|thumb|Fastrack 510 being installed in Hawaii]]\nHawaii- 2.4&nbsp;mW array at Hawaii Airports\n\nSt. Maarteen- 800&nbsp;kW array\n\nDorado, Puerto Rico- 872&nbsp;kW array\n\nRenton, Washington- 1.125&nbsp;mW array\n\n==Products==\n[[File:A&R IKEA-150.jpg|thumb|Sollega]]\nThe current racking system provided by Sollega is the Fastrack 510 which is sourced and made in the US. It can mount both 5\u00b0 and 10\u00b0 arrays and is designed to be anchored using anchors and/or ballast. The individual units are made out of lightweight high density polyethylene plastic (HDPE). The material uses a minimum of 35% recycled content resulting in a lower carbon footprint.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sollega.com/ Official site]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Solar energy companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{third-party|date=August 2017}}{{notability|1=Companies|date=August 2017}}}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Sollega\n| logo             = Sollega logo w tag 2013 RM.png\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2009}}\n| location_city    = [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| key_people       = Elie Rothschild, CEO<br />Lee Rothschild, Director of Engineering <br />Juan Carlos Chavez, Solar PV System Designer <br /> Bryan Weinberg, Account Manager \n| industry         = Solar Racking\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.sollega.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Sollega''' is a US based solar racking company that provides solutions for flat mount and ground mount solar arrays for commercial and industrial use. Sollega operates out of The [[Mission District]] in San Francisco, California.\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded in 2009 by Elie Rothschild who had already been in the solar industry for 7 years. Sollega proposed a cheaper alternative to the conventional metal mounting systems. The company produced its first racking system Instarack 15\u00b0 followed by the Instarack 10\u00b0. These were replaced with the updated Fastrack 5\u00b0 in 2012. In 2014 this was replaced by the current system, the Fastrack 510.\n\n==Major Installations==\n[[File:OCC2.jpg|thumb|Fastrack 510 being installed in Hawaii]]\nHawaii- 2.4&nbsp;mW array at Hawaii Airports\n\nSt. Maarteen- 800&nbsp;kW array\n\nDorado, Puerto Rico- 872&nbsp;kW array\n\nRenton, Washington- 1.125&nbsp;mW array\n\n==Products==\n[[File:A&R IKEA-150.jpg|thumb|Sollega]]\nThe current racking system provided by Sollega is the Fastrack 510 which is sourced and made in the US. It can mount both 5\u00b0 and 10\u00b0 arrays and is designed to be anchored using anchors and/or ballast. The individual units are made out of lightweight high density polyethylene plastic (HDPE). The material uses a minimum of 35% recycled content resulting in a lower carbon footprint.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sollega.com/ Official site]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Solar energy companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "68.195.21.156", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sollega"}
{"title_page": "True Detective (season 1)", "text_new": "{{short description|Season of television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number = 1\n |bgcolour = #9aaaa5\n |image = True Detective season 1.png\n |image_size = 250px\n |caption = Blu-ray cover\n |starring  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Matthew McConaughey]]\n* [[Woody Harrelson]]\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]]\n* [[Michael Potts (actor)|Michael Potts]]\n* [[Tory Kittles]]}}\n |country = United States\n |network = [[HBO]]\n |first_aired = {{Start date|2014|1|12}}\n |last_aired = {{End date|2014|3|9}}\n |num_episodes = 8\n |episode_list = List of True Detective episodes\n}}\n\nThe first season of ''[[True Detective]]'', an American [[anthology series|anthology]] [[crime drama]] television series created by [[Nic Pizzolatto]], premiered on January 12, 2014, on the premium cable network [[HBO]]. The principal cast consisted of [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Woody Harrelson]], [[Michelle Monaghan]], [[Michael Potts (actor)|Michael Potts]], and [[Tory Kittles]]. The season had eight episodes, and its initial airing concluded on March 9, 2014. As an anthology, each ''True Detective'' season has its own self-contained story, following a disparate set of characters in various settings.\n\nConstructed as a [[nonlinear narrative]], season one focuses on [[Louisiana State Police]] homicide detectives [[Rust Cohle|Rustin \"Rust\" Cohle]] (McConaughey) and Martin \"Marty\" Hart (Harrelson), who investigated the murder of prostitute Dora Lange in 1995.  Seventeen years later, they must revisit the investigation, along with several other unsolved crimes. During this time, Hart's infidelity threatens his marriage to Maggie (Monaghan), and Cohle struggles to cope with his troubled past. ''True Detective''{{'s}} first season explores themes of [[philosophical pessimism]], masculinity, and Christianity; critics have analyzed the show's portrayal of women, its [[auteur theory|auteurist]] sensibility, and the influence of [[comics]] and [[Weird fiction|weird]] [[horror fiction]] on its narrative.\n\nPizzolatto initially conceived ''True Detective'' as a novel, but felt it was more suitable for television. The episodes, directed by [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]], were filmed in Louisiana over a three-month period. The series received positive reviews from critics and was cited as one of the strongest dramas of the 2014 television season. It was a candidate for numerous television awards, including a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]] and a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Television Film]], and won several other honors for writing, cinematography, direction, and acting.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{see also|List of True Detective episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background=#9aaaa5 |overall=6 |season=6 |title=24 |director=16 |writer=23 |airdate=15 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = [[The Long Bright Dark]]\n |DirectedBy = {{nowrap|[[Cary Joji Fukunaga]]}}\n |WrittenBy = {{nowrap|[[Nic Pizzolatto]]}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|12}}\n |Viewers = 2.33<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/14/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-true-detective-ax-men-shameless-more/229014/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' Wins Night, 'True Detective', 'Ax Men', 'Shameless' & More |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=January 14, 2014 |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104201423/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/14/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-true-detective-ax-men-shameless-more/229014/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = [[Vermilion Parish, Louisiana]], January 3, 1995. State homicide detectives Martin \"Marty\" Hart ([[Woody Harrelson]]) and [[Rust Cohle|Rustin \"Rust\" Cohle]] ([[Matthew McConaughey]]) investigate the murder of a prostitute, 28-year-old Dora Lange. Her corpse is found posed as if in prayer, her head is crowned with deer antlers, and her body is surrounded by twig latticeworks closely resembling [[Cajun]] bird traps. Hart and Cohle turn to a five-year-old missing-persons case of a child named Marie Fontenot. Around the same time, another child claimed to have been chased through the woods by a \"green-eared spaghetti monster.\" At the insistence of his wife Maggie ([[Michelle Monaghan]]), Hart invites Cohle to dinner, but is infuriated when Cohle arrives drunk. While following up on the Fontenot disappearance, they discover another twig latticework.\n----\nSeventeen years later in May 2012, Hart and Cohle are separately interviewed about the Lange investigation by detectives Thomas Papania ([[Tory Kittles]]) and Maynard Gilbough ([[Michael Potts (actor)|Michael Potts]]). Hart and Cohle have not spoken since an altercation in 2002. The crime scene of a recently slain woman closely resembles the Lange murder scene, suggesting that despite Cohle and Hart's claims of apprehending the killer in 1995, the killer may remain at large.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Seeing Things\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|19}}\n |Viewers = 1.67<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/22/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-shameless-true-detective-girls-more/230965/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' Wins Night, 'Keeping Up With the Kardashians', 'Shameless', 'True Detective', 'Girls' & More |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=January 22, 2014 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104201834/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/22/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-shameless-true-detective-girls-more/230965/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = 1995. Animosity between Cohle and Hart flares after Cohle suspects Hart is cheating on Maggie. Reverend Billy Lee Tuttle ([[Jay O. Sanders]]), a celebrated evangelist and cousin of the governor, advocates a police task force focusing on \"anti-Christian crimes,\" including the Lange murder. Hart and Cohle's investigation leads them to a remote ranch harboring runaway girls who work there as prostitutes. They find Lange's diary, which contains repeated references to \"[[Carcosa]]\" and a \"[[The King in Yellow|Yellow King]],\" at the ranch. In the wreckage of a burnt-out church Lange attended, they find a wall painting depicting a human figure wearing deer antlers.\n----\nIn 2012, Cohle reflects on his daughter's death in a car accident, which led to the collapse of his marriage and his spending four years as an undercover narcotics investigator. His undercover career ended with a lethal gunfight, after which he was hospitalized in a psychiatric institution. After his release, Cohle requested a job in homicide and was partnered with Hart. Cohle reveals that he experiences brief, intermittent episodes of visual hallucinations caused by years of drug use while working as an undercover officer. Shots from 1995 show that Cohle occasionally suffers these hallucinations when he is with Hart, but he does not discuss them. Hart is now divorced from Maggie for reasons unrevealed.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = The Locked Room\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|26}}\n |Viewers = 1.93<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/28/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-live-from-the-red-carpet-curse-of-oak-island-sister-wives-more/232422/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Real Housewives of Atlanta' Wins Night + 'Live From the Red Carpet', 'Curse of Oak Island', 'Sister Wives' & More |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=January 28, 2014 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104202255/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/28/sunday-cable-ratings-real-housewives-of-atlanta-wins-night-live-from-the-red-carpet-curse-of-oak-island-sister-wives-more/232422/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = 1995. Hart and Cohle, after speaking with pastor Joel Theriot ([[Shea Whigham]]), learn that Lange was sometimes seen at church with a tall man with distinctive facial scarring. Their investigation continues in the face of pressure to turn the case over to Tuttle's new task force. Hart enters a jealous rage when he discovers his mistress Lisa ([[Alexandra Daddario]]) with another man. While researching old investigations, Cohle identifies symbols similar to the Lange case in the death of Rianne Olivier, which was classified as accidental. Hart and Cohle visit Light of the Way Academy, a religious school run by Tuttle that Olivier attended, but find it abandoned save for a groundskeeper on a riding lawnmower, whom Cohle questions. They discover that Olivier's boyfriend, Reggie Ledoux ([[Charles Halford]]) is an ex-con who was a cellmate of Dora Lange's ex-husband, Charlie, and has since skipped parole. The detectives put out an [[All-points bulletin|APB]] on Reggie Ledoux.\n----\n2012. The interviews continue, revealing Hart's questionable moral views and Cohle's nihilistic views of humanity.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Who Goes There\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|9}}\n |Viewers = 1.99<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/11/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-tops-night-real-housewives-of-atlanta-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-more/236089/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Tops Night + 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'Keeping Up With the Kardashians' & More |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=July 17, 2015 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104202749/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/11/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-tops-night-real-housewives-of-atlanta-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-more/236089/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In 1995, Charlie Lange ([[Brad Carter]]) says he showed pictures of Dora to Ledoux. Hart tracks down an associate of Ledoux's and forces him to reveal Ledoux's [[Methamphetamine|meth]] operation with the Iron Crusaders, a biker gang out of East Texas. Cohle, who had been a member of the gang while undercover, takes personal leave to infiltrate it, saying he needs to visit his dying father. Lisa reveals the affair to Maggie, who leaves the house with their daughters. Hart confronts Maggie at her workplace; Cohle extricates him from a standoff with security officers. Cohle's contact in the Iron Crusaders, Ginger ([[Joseph Sikora]]), promises access to the gang's meth supply in exchange for Cohle's (who is known to the gang as \"Crash\") help robbing a rival gang. The robbery goes badly, with fatalities on both sides and rising chaos in the rival gang's neighborhood. Cohle is forced to take Ginger prisoner and escape in Hart's car.\n----\nIn 2012, Hart and Cohle both maintain the story of Cohle's sick father in the face of skeptical questioning by Papania and Gilbough.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = {{nowrap|The Secret Fate of All Life}}\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|16}}\n |Viewers = 2.25<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/19/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-nba-all-star-game-real-housewives-of-atlanta-true-detective-shameless-more/238060/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, NBA All Star Game, 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'True Detective', 'Shameless' & More |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=July 17, 2015 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104203224/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/19/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-nba-all-star-game-real-housewives-of-atlanta-true-detective-shameless-more/238060/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In 1995, Ginger introduces Cohle to DeWall Ledoux ([[\u00d3lafur Darri \u00d3lafsson]]), Reggie's cousin and meth-cooking partner. DeWall refuses to do business with Cohle, but unwittingly leads him and Hart to a meth lab hidden in the bayou. There, Hart apprehends Reggie Ledoux, who makes cryptic statements about \"Carcosa\". Hart kills Reggie in a rage after discovering two kidnapped and abused children, a brother and sister, in the compound. DeWall flees but dies after triggering a homemade booby trap. Hart and Cohle plant evidence to make it look as though an intense shootout has taken place, a scenario they report to a police investigation. They are hailed as heroes at the police station and in the press, and they receive commendations and promotions.\n----\nBy 2002, Hart and Maggie have reconciled and Cohle is dating again. While Cohle is consulting on a police interrogation, the prisoner asks for a [[plea bargain]] in exchange for information about Dora Lange's killer, who he claims is still at large and killing. He mentions the \"Yellow King,\" which gets Cohle's attention. The prisoner kills himself in his cell before Cohle can investigate his claims. Cohle returns to Light of the Way Academy, where he finds dozens of twig sculptures and dark imagery on the walls.\n----\nIn 2012, Papania and Gilbough tell Hart they suspect that Cohle, who they allege conveniently led Hart to every clue or lead in the case, has been orchestrating the killings. Cohle is also a person of interest in Rev. Billy Lee Tuttle's suspicious death two years earlier, which was around the time Cohle returned to Louisiana. Cohle walks out of his interview after the detectives accuse him.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Haunted Houses\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|23}}\n |Viewers = 2.64<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/25/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-real-housewives-of-atlanta-more/239737/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, + 'Talking Dead', 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'True Detective' & More |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=February 25, 2014 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104203900/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/25/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-real-housewives-of-atlanta-more/239737/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In 2002, Cohle links a series of missing persons to Tuttle-funded schools. A former pastor in Tuttle's ministries claims Tuttle covered up child molestation. Ledoux's surviving victim, now institutionalized with [[catatonia|regressive catatonia]], tells Cohle about a third attacker\u2014a giant man with scars\u2014and begins screaming when Cohle asks her about the man's face. Tuttle complains to the police department following a tense meeting with Cohle, who has been warned to cease his investigation and is suspended from duty. Hart begins an affair with Beth ([[Lili Simmons]]), a former underage prostitute whom he interviewed in 1995 while working on the Lange case. After Maggie discovers the new affair, she tempts a drunk Cohle and has sex with him. After she tells Hart about it, he and Cohle fight in the police station parking lot. Cohle quits the police force immediately after the fight.\n----\nIn 2012, Papania and Gilbough interview Maggie, who deflects their questions. Hart walks out of his interview in response to Papania and Gilbough's accusations against Cohle. Cohle seeks out Hart and they agree to meet and talk.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = After You've Gone\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|3|2}}\n |Viewers = 2.34<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/03/04/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-true-detective-oscars-red-carpet-girls-more/241767/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, 'Talking Dead', 'True Detective', Oscars Red Carpet, 'Girls' & More |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=March 4, 2014 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104204428/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/03/04/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-true-detective-oscars-red-carpet-girls-more/241767/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|ShortSummary = In 2012, Cohle presents Hart with evidence of a cult he believes is responsible for the disappearance of dozens of women and children along the coast in Louisiana. Among the evidence is a videotape, which Cohle stole from a safe in Rev. Tuttle's home, of men in costumes and masks ritualistically raping and murdering Marie Fontenot (the missing-child case they briefly investigated in 1995). Cohle denies killing Tuttle, speculating that others did it to prevent Tuttle from being blackmailed over the tape. Hart, shaken from watching the videotape, agrees to join the investigation. They learn that Tuttle had an illegitimate half-brother with the surname Childress, whose son had scars on his face. They also learn that their former colleague Steve Geraci ([[Michael Harney]]) was ordered by his boss Ted Childress\u2014then the sheriff of Vermilion Parish\u2014to cut short his investigation of Fontenot's disappearance. Hart and Cohle accost Geraci to coerce the details from him, threatening him if he should try to go to the authorities or have them arrested. Gilbough and Papania ask the same groundskeeper Cohle encountered at Light of the Way Academy in 1995 for directions to the burnt-out church. They drive off without noticing the lower part of his face is heavily scarred.\n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|True Detective (season 1)\n |EpisodeNumber = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Form and Void\n |DirectedBy = Cary Joji Fukunaga\n |WrittenBy = Nic Pizzolatto\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|3|9}}\n |Viewers = 3.52<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/03/11/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-the-real-housewives-of-atlanta-true-detective-more/243520/ |title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Wins Night, 'Talking Dead', 'The Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'True Detective' & More |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=March 11, 2014 |publisher=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104204832/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/03/11/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-wins-night-talking-dead-the-real-housewives-of-atlanta-true-detective-more/243520/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|ShortSummary = In 2012, the \"man with the scars\" ([[Glenn Fleshler]]) is shown living in a large house in squalor with a female relative ([[Ann Dowd]]) with whom he has a sexual relationship. He speaks cryptically in multiple accents, and keeps his father's decaying corpse in a shed on his property. Later, he goes to work painting a school, where he watches children on the playground. Hart and Cohle extract details from Geraci by showing him the Fontenot tape. Hart thinks the \"green-eared spaghetti monster\" may have been the scarred man covered in green paint after painting a house in Dora Lange's neighborhood in 1995. They trace the paint job to a small business owned by William Childress that employed a man with scars on his face. They visit William Childress's home\u2014the house where the \"man with the scars\" lives. Cohle pursues the man, William Childress's son Errol, through a labyrinth of trees and tunnels that Errol identifies as Carcosa. At the end, Cohle discovers an [[Cult image|idol]] draped in yellow and covered in skulls, and briefly sees a hallucination of a sort of spiraling vortex. Cohle is then attacked by Errol. Hart, after detaining the woman and calling the police, discovers William's decaying corpse and runs to Cohle's aid. Hart and Cohle fight Errol; they are both severely wounded, but Cohle manages to kill Errol via a gunshot to the head. Papania and Gilbough arrive with reinforcements as Hart aids Cohle. While Hart and Cohle recover in hospital, Papania and Gilbough connect Errol to dozens of missing-person cases and murders, including Dora Lange's, finding several bodies buried in the yard. The Tuttles escape prosecution, but are publicly disgraced. Hart breaks down in tears when Maggie and their daughters visit him. Cohle reveals that during his ordeal, he felt the loving presence of his dead father and daughter, and the experience has given his life renewed purpose. The two detectives reflect on the ongoing universal battle between light and dark. \n |LineColor = 9aaaa5\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Matthew McConaughey]] as Detective [[Rust Cohle|Rustin \"Rust\" Cohle]]\n* [[Woody Harrelson]] as Detective Martin \"Marty\" Hart\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]] as Maggie Hart\n* [[Michael Potts (actor)|Michael Potts]] as Detective Maynard Gilbough\n* [[Tory Kittles]] as Detective Thomas Papania\n\n===Recurring cast===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Kevin Dunn]] as Major Ken Quesada\n*[[Alexandra Daddario]] as Lisa Tragnetti\n*[[Michael Harney]] as Sheriff Steve Geraci\n*[[Elizabeth Reaser]] as Laurie Perkins\n*[[J. D. Evermore]] as Detective Bobby Lutz\n*[[Madison Wolfe]] as young Audrey Hart\n:*[[Erin Moriarty (actress)|Erin Moriarty]] as teenage Audrey Hart\n*Meghan Wolfe as young Macie Hart\n:*[[Brighton Sharbino]] as teenage Macie Hart\n*Don Yesso as Commander Speece\n*[[Brad Carter]] as Charlie Lange\n*[[Lili Simmons]] as Beth\n*[[Jay O. Sanders]] as Billy Lee Tuttle\n*[[Shea Whigham]] as Joel Theriot\n*[[Glenn Fleshler]] as Errol Childress\n*[[Charles Halford]] as Reggie Ledoux\n*[[Joseph Sikora]] as Ginger\n*[[Paul Ben-Victor]] as Major Leroy Salter\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Conception===\n\nBefore creating ''[[True Detective]]'', [[Nic Pizzolatto]] had taught at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], [[DePauw University]], and the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=nola/> Inspired by [[HBO]]'s series ''[[The Wire]]'', ''[[The Sopranos]]'', and ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'',<ref name=beast1/> he began working on a short story collection that he later published as ''Between Here and the Yellow Sea'' in 2006.<ref name=nola/> He published a novel, ''Galveston'', in 2010, and began trying to write for television. His earlier attempts at television writing were unsuccessful because of a lack of money.<ref name=\"beast1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/04/inside-the-obsessive-strange-mind-of-true-detective-s-nic-pizzolatto.html |title=Inside the Obsessive, Strange Mind of True Detective's Nic Pizzolatto |last=Romano |first=Andrew |date=April 4, 2014 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |publisher=[[The Newsweek Daily Beast Company]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104205420/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/04/inside-the-obsessive-strange-mind-of-true-detective-s-nic-pizzolatto.html |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> Pizzolatto's first major gig in television writing came in 2011, as a screenwriter for [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]'s series ''[[The Killing (U.S. TV series)|The Killing]]''. He credits the show with giving him a glimpse of the inner workings of the television industry. Pizzolatto grew increasingly dissatisfied with the series' creative direction, and left two weeks into staff writing sessions for [[The Killing (season 2)|its second season]].<ref name=nola/>\n\n''True Detective'' was intended to be a novel, but once the project took definite form, Pizzolatto thought the narrative's shifts in time and perspective made it more suitable for television.<ref name=\"nola\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/tv/index.ssf/2013/07/nic_pizzolatto_new_orleans-bor.html |title=Nic Pizzolatto, New Orleans-born novelist, discusses HBO's upcoming 'True Detective' |last=Walker |first=Dave |date=July 7, 2013 |website=[[The Times-Picayune]] |publisher=Ricky Matthews |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104191010/http://www.nola.com/tv/index.ssf/2013/07/nic_pizzolatto_new_orleans-bor.html |archive-date=November 4, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=hr/> He pitched an adaptation of ''Galveston'', and from May to July 2010 he developed six screenplays, including an early, 90-page draft of the ''True Detective'' [[The Long Bright Dark|pilot]] script.<ref name=nola/><ref name=beast1/> Pizzolatto secured a development deal with HBO for a potential pilot series shortly thereafter.<ref name=nola/> He wrote a second ''True Detective'' script soon after his departure from ''The Killing'' thanks to the support of production company and manager [[Anonymous Content]],<ref name=nola/> which ultimately produced and developed the project in-house.<ref name=\"True Detectives\" /> By April 2012, following a heated bidding period, HBO commissioned eight episodes of ''True Detective''.<ref name=\"True Detectives\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/hbo-picks-up-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-series-true-detective/ |title=HBO Picks Up Matthew-Woody Series 'True Detective' With Eight-Episode Orders |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=April 30, 2012 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104210505/http://deadline.com/2012/04/hbo-picks-up-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-series-true-detective-264567/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> Pizzolatto did not hire a writing staff because he believed a collaborative approach would not work with his isolated, novelistic process, and that a group would not achieve his desired result.<ref name=lamag/> After working alone for about three months, the final copy of the project script was 500 pages long.<ref name=\"lamag\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/qa-true-detective-creator-nic-pizzolatto-is-a-one-man-writing-army/ |title=Q&A: \"True Detective\" Creator Nic Pizzolatto is a One-Man Writing Army |last=Duelund |first=Theis |date=January 4, 2014 |website=[[Los Angeles (magazine)|Los Angeles]] |publisher=[[Emmis Communications]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104205640/http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/qa-true-detective-creator-nic-pizzolatto-is-a-one-man-writing-army/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://politiken.dk/magasinet/fortaelling/ECE2373439/til-masterclass-med-mr-true-detective/ |title=Til masterclass med Mr. True Detective |last=Navae |first=Helene |date=August 23, 2014 |website=[[Politiken]] |publisher=[[JP/Politikens Hus]] |language=Danish |trans-title=To master class with Mr. True Detective |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104210145/http://politiken.dk/magasinet/fortaelling/ECE2373439/til-masterclass-med-mr-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cast and crew===\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 360\n| footer = [[Matthew McConaughey]] (left), [[Woody Harrelson]] (middle) and [[Michelle Monaghan]] (right) star in the first season of ''True Detective''.\n\n| image1 = Matthew McConaughey - Goldene Kamera 2014 - Berlin.jpg\n| image2 = Woody_Harrelson_October_2016.jpg\n| image3 = Michelle Monaghan at TIFF.jpg\n}}\n\nBecause the series is an anthology, each season has a self-contained narrative, following a disparate set of characters in various settings.<ref name=\"nola\" /> Pizzolatto began contemplating the lead roles while he was pitching the series to networks in early 2012.<ref name=nola/> ''True Detective''{{'s}} anthology format required actors to commit to only a single season, so Pizzolatto was able to attract film stars who normally avoid television series because of their busy schedules.<ref name=lamag/> [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Matthew McConaughey]] were among the actors Pizzolatto considered for star billing. McConaughey, who had recently finished filming ''[[Killer Joe (film)|Killer Joe]]'' (2011), was contracted well before HBO commissioned the season.<ref name=\"hr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/true-detective-five-things-know-669722 |title='True Detective': Five Things to Know About HBO's New Cop Drama |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=January 9, 2014 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104210900/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/true-detective-five-things-know-669722 |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> Impressed with his performance in ''[[The Lincoln Lawyer (film)|The Lincoln Lawyer]]'' (2011), Pizzolatto at first assigned him to play Hart, but McConaughey convinced him to give him the part of Cohle.<ref name=\"salon\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/01/09/true_detective_director_cary_fukunaga_explains_the_shows_dark_humor/ |title='True Detective' director Cary Fukunaga explains the show's dark humor |last=Drumming |first=Neil |date=January 9, 2014 |website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104211604/http://www.salon.com/2014/01/09/true_detective_director_cary_fukunaga_explains_the_shows_dark_humor/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> When asked in a ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' interview about his decision to switch parts, the actor replied, \"I wanted to get in that dude's head. The obsession, the island of a man\u2014I'm always looking for a guy who monologues. It's something really important as I feel I'm going into my better work.\"<ref name=\"variety\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/dark-character-draws-mcconaughey-to-hbos-noir-miniseries-1201105443/ |title=Matthew McConaughey on 'True Detective': 'I Wanted to Get in That Dude's Head' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=February 18, 2014 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104212200/http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/dark-character-draws-mcconaughey-to-hbos-noir-miniseries-1201105443/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> To prepare for the role, McConaughey created a 450-page analysis\u2014the \"Four Stages of Rustin Cohle\"\u2014to study his character's evolution during the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/mcconaughey-reveals-the-four-stages-of-true-detective-rustin-cohle-20140304 |title=Matthew McConaughey Reveals the Four Stages of 'True Detective' Rustin Cohle |last=Ringen |first=Jonathan |date=March 4, 2014 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104212742/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/mcconaughey-reveals-the-four-stages-of-true-detective-rustin-cohle-20140304 |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarrelson was the season's next significant casting choice, brought on to play Hart at McConaughey's request.<ref name=\"rs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/q-a-matthew-mcconaughey-talks-true-detective-20140303 |title=Matthew McConaughey on 'True Detective,' His Pal Woody, McConaissance |last=Ringen |first=Jonathan |date=March 3, 2014 |website=Rolling Stone |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104213311/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/q-a-matthew-mcconaughey-talks-true-detective-20140303 |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/mar/21/true-detective-cary-fukunaga-interview |title=True Detective: how we made the most talked-about TV show of the year |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |date=March 21, 2014 |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian News and Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104213811/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/mar/21/true-detective-cary-fukunaga-interview |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> Harrelson stated that he joined ''True Detective'' partly because he wanted to work with certain people involved in the project, with whom he had previously collaborated in the 2012 HBO film ''[[Game Change (film)|Game Change]]''.<ref name=\"col2\">{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/true-detective-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-interview/ |title=Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson Talk True Detective, Why They Agreed to Do a TV Show, Working with Each Other, and More |last=Radish |first=Christina |date=January 4, 2014 |publisher=Collider |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104214101/http://collider.com/true-detective-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-interview/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> [[Michelle Monaghan]] agreed to play the season's female lead, Maggie, because she felt compelled by the direction of the plot and her character's story arc.<ref name=\"col1\">{{Cite web |url=https://collider.com/michelle-monaghan-true-detective-interview/#uHDEVjWPWS6XPdLV.99 |title=Michelle Monaghan Talks True Detective, Joining the Show, Working with Cary Fukunaga, the Mood on Set, Future Projects, and More |last=Radish |first=Christina |date=February 12, 2014 |publisher=Collider |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104214427/http://collider.com/michelle-monaghan-true-detective-interview/ |archive-date=November 4, 2015}}</ref> [[Michael Potts (actor)|Michael Potts]] and [[Tory Kittles]] completed the principal cast, playing detectives Maynard Gilbough and Thomas Papania, respectively.<ref name=\"td2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/01/texas-chainsaws-alexandra-daddario-twilight-sagas-elizabeth-reaser-2-others-join-new-hbo-series-true-detective/ |title='Texas Chainsaw's Alexandra Daddario, 'Twilight Saga's Elizabeth Reaser, 2 'Wire' Alums Join New HBO Series 'True Detective' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=January 14, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105133616/http://deadline.com/2013/01/texas-chainsaws-alexandra-daddario-twilight-sagas-elizabeth-reaser-2-others-join-new-hbo-series-true-detective-404353/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2013/02/hbo-series-true-detective-amcs-the-killing-add-to-casts-435209/ |title='HBO Series 'True Detective', AMC's 'The Killing' Add To Casts |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=January 14, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105134056/http://deadline.com/2013/02/hbo-series-true-detective-amcs-the-killing-add-to-casts-435209/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Major supporting roles in ''True Detective''{{'s}} first season include [[Kevin Dunn]] as Major Ken Quesada, [[Alexandra Daddario]] as Lisa Tragnetti, and [[Brad Carter]] as Charlie Lange.<ref name=td2/>\n\nPizzolatto narrowed his search for a suitable director to [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]], whom he knew from Anonymous Content, and [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]. Fukunaga was formally appointed as director after I\u00f1\u00e1rritu pulled out of the project due to film commitments.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-true-detective-pizzolatto-borrelli-20140122-column.html#page=1 |title=True voice brings 'True Detective' to life |last=Borrelli |first=Christopher |date=January 22, 2014 |website=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher=Tony W. Hunter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105134635/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-true-detective-pizzolatto-borrelli-20140122-column.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"beast2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/26/true-detective-director-cary-fukunaga-s-journey-from-pro-snowboarder-to-hollywood-s-most-wanted.html |title=True Detective Director Cary Fukunaga's Journey from Pro Snowboarder to Hollywood's Most Wanted |last=Stern |first=Marlow |date=February 26, 2014 |website=The Daily Beast |publisher=The Newsweek Daily Beast Company |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105135043/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/26/true-detective-director-cary-fukunaga-s-journey-from-pro-snowboarder-to-hollywood-s-most-wanted.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> In preparation for his work on the series, Fukunaga spent time with a homicide detective of the [[Louisiana State Police]]'s Criminal Investigations Division to develop an accurate depiction of a 1990s homicide detective's work.<ref name=\"interviewmag\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/cary-fukunaga-true-detective/#_ |title=True Director |last=Brown |first=Emma |website=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |publisher=Dan Ragone |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105135421/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/culture/cary-fukunaga-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Fukunaga recruited [[Adam Arkapaw]], director of photography of ''[[Top of the Lake]]'', as project cinematographer. Arkapaw came to the director's attention for his work in ''[[Animal Kingdom (film)|Animal Kingdom]]'' (2010) and ''[[Snowtown (film)|Snowtown]]'' (2011), and was hired after the two negotiated a deal at a meeting in [[San Francisco]].<ref name=\"kodak\">{{Cite web |url=http://motion.kodak.com/motion/Publications/InCamera/HBO_s_True_Detective_Elevates_the_Television_Drama.htm |title=HBO's True Detective Elevates the Television Drama |date=November 20, 2013 |website=InCamera |publisher=[[Kodak]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105140408/http://motion.kodak.com/motion/Publications/InCamera/HBO_s_True_Detective_Elevates_the_Television_Drama.htm |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Alex DiGerlando, who Fukunaga had worked with on [[Benh Zeitlin]]{{'s}} ''Glory at Sea'' in 2008, was appointed as the production designer. Fukunaga said in an interview, \"I knew what Alex accomplished in the swamps of Louisiana and given some money, how much more amazing he could be in building sets that would just be used for one or two days and be abandoned again.\"<ref name=fc/>\n\n===Filming===\n\nInitially, ''True Detective''{{'s}} first season was due to shoot in [[Arkansas]], but Pizzolatto later chose to film in [[Louisiana]] to take advantage of [[Film industry in Louisiana|state tax incentives]] and the area's distinctive landscape:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cenlamar.com/2014/01/16/exclusive-nic-pizzolattos-louisiana/ |title=Exclusive: Nic Pizzolatto's Louisiana |last=White, Jr. |first=Lamar |date=January 16, 2014 |publisher=CenLamar |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105181855/http://cenlamar.com/2014/01/16/exclusive-nic-pizzolattos-louisiana/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> \"There's a contradictory nature to the place and a sort of sinister quality underneath it all&nbsp;...&nbsp;everything lives under layers of concealment. The woods are thick and dark and impenetrable. On the other hand you have the beauty of it all from a distance.\"<ref name=lamag/> Principal photography took three months (between 100 and 110 days),<ref name=\"fc\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.fastcocreate.com/3024587/director-cary-fukunaga-on-conjuring-the-louisiana-noir-of-true-detective |title=Director Cary Fukunaga on Conjuring the Louisiana Noir of 'True Detective' |last=Hart |first=Hugh |date=January 6, 2014 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Fast Company, Inc. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105190013/http://www.fastcocreate.com/3024587/director-cary-fukunaga-on-conjuring-the-louisiana-noir-of-true-detective |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> from January to June 2013.<ref name=kodak/> Approximately five minutes of film were shot per day.<ref name=kodak/> Production staff constructed various set pieces, among them a scorched chapel, Joel Theriot's [[tent revival]], and the Louisiana State Criminal Investigations Division offices, the last of which they built inside an abandoned light bulb warehouse near [[Elmwood, Louisiana|Elmwood]].<ref name=art/> For the Dora Lange crime scene, the crew filmed exterior shots at a remote sugarcane field outside [[Erath, Louisiana|Erath]] which, because it was partially burned, inspired what DiGerlando called a \"moody and atmospheric\" backdrop for the corresponding interior scenes.<ref name=\"art\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-alex-digerlando-set-design-props-interview.html |title=Devil's Nests and Beer-Can Men: The Origins of 13 True Detective Set Pieces |last=Martin |first=Denise |date=March 6, 2014 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |publisher=New York Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105190544/http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-alex-digerlando-set-design-props-interview.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> The scene in which Cohle, taking Ginger hostage, escapes a housing complex amidst gunfire, was captured in [[Bridge City, Louisiana|Bridge City]] as a single six-minute [[tracking shot]], a technique Fukunaga had employed in ''[[Sin Nombre (2009 film)|Sin Nombre]]'' (2009) and ''[[Jane Eyre (2011 film)|Jane Eyre]]'' (2011).<ref name=Mtv/><ref name=\"arch\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.archdaily.com/493920/interiors-true-detective |title=Interiors: True Detective |last=Ahi |first=Mehruss |last2=Karaoghlanian |first2=Armen |date=April 8, 2014 |publisher=[[ArchDaily]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925032321/http://www.archdaily.com/493920/interiors-true-detective |archive-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> Shot in seven takes, preparation for the scene was extensive and demanding: McConaughey trained with Mark Norby to master a fighting style for his character,<ref name=\"Mtv\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1722001/true-detective-long-take/ |title='True Detective': How did they pull off that final shot? |last=Sullivan |first=Kevin |date=February 7, 2014 |publisher=[[MTV News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925031516/http://www.mtv.com/news/1722001/true-detective-long-take/ |archive-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> and the nature of the shoot required a team of stunt coordinators, make-up artists, and special effects crew on hand during its entire course.<ref name=arch/> Elsewhere, shooting took place at the old Kenner High School campus<ref name=art/> and nineteenth-century [[Fort Macomb]], located outside [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-finale-production-designer-fort-maze.html |title=True Detective's Production Designer on the Fort |last=Martin |first=Denise |date=March 10, 2014 |website=New York |publisher=New York Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105190839/http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-finale-production-designer-fort-maze.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe filming schedule was not organized in the episode sequence, which made managing the logistics much more challenging.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/interview-cary-fukunaga-on-hbo-series-true-detective-starring-matthew-mcconaughey-and-woody-harrelson-20130712 |title=Interview: Cary Fukunaga Talks HBO's 'True Detective,' Says Child Soldier Film 'Beasts Of No Nation' Coming Next |last=Kiang |first=Jessica |date=July 12, 2013 |publisher=Indiewire |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105191253/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/interview-cary-fukunaga-on-hbo-series-true-detective-starring-matthew-mcconaughey-and-woody-harrelson-20130712# |archive-date=November 5, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015}}</ref> The entire season was shot on [[35mm movie film|35 mm film]],<ref name=\"td\">{{Cite AV media |title=\"Making True Detective\" featurette |last=[[Cary Joji Fukunaga]] (director) |publisher=[[HBO]] |year=2014 |time=7:51\u20137:53 |medium=[[Blu-ray]]}}</ref> which the production staff chose to achieve a certain texture, as well as a \"nostalgic\" quality.<ref name=kodak/> The season was filmed using a [[Panavision|Panavision Millennium XL2 camera]], and the choice of lens corresponded to the period when a scene took place. Scenes set in 1995 and 2002 were captured with Panavision PVintage lenses, which produced a softer image because they were made of recycled, low-contrast glass. As these scenes were written as a reflection of Cohle and Hart's memory, production sought to make them as cinematic as possible, to reflect what Arkapaw called \"the fragmentation of their lucid imaginations back through their past.\"<ref name=kodak/> To achieve this, they relied on wider lenses to exaggerate composition.<ref name=kodak/> The 2012 scenes were shot with Panavision Primo lenses: the visual palette in comparison was sharper and had much more contrast, lending a \"modern, crisp feeling\" to the images, and, according to Arkapaw, pulling \"characters out from their environments to hopefully help audiences get inside their heads.\"<ref name=kodak/>\n\n===Art design===\n[[File:TrueDetectivedigitaldouble.jpg|thumb|left|The design team used an assortment of low poly meshes to develop a 3D landscape for the show's title sequence, which were later meticulously superimposed. Digital doubles (such as this one of Hart shown in the upper left frame) were created in some cases to allow more texture.<ref name=aott/>|alt=This image illustrates the superimposition of True Detective's title sequence in intermediate stages compared to the final product.]]\n\nJoshua Walsh was responsible for creating ''True Detective''{{'s}} artwork. His work for the show consists of over 100 individual \"devil's nests\"\u2014twig sculptures created by the killer\u2014along with wall paintings and miniature sculptures of men made of beer cans, among others.<ref name=art/> According to DiGerlando, Walsh's interests in hunting and taxidermy made him \"the perfect dude for the job\".<ref name=art/> A blueprint for the devil's nests was not well established in the script, other than specifications that the structures be able to stand on their own and feature a spiral motif. DiGerlando and Walsh went with a tripod design that showed a spiral when viewed from the base, and contained ladder-like crossing elements that symbolized the killer's desire to ascend to a dark [[Plane (esotericism)|spiritual plane]]. Each design had subtle differences from one another.<ref name=art/> DiGerlando cited the work of [[Henry Darger]] and [[James Charles Castle]] as strong stylistic influences and sought a primitive look for the sculptures, one that revealed the workings of a man with \"some deep inner urge to express himself\".<ref name=art/> To reflect this, Walsh built devil's nests using mud, secondhand children's clothing, reeds, roots, and other materials he felt the killer would use.<ref name=art/>\n\nThe season's title sequence was a collaboration between director Patrick Clair, his [[Santa Monica]]-based studio Elastic, his [[Sydney]]-based studio Antibody, and [[Brisbane]]-based company Breeder.<ref name=\"aott\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.artofthetitle.com/title/true-detective/ |title=True Detective (2014) |last=Perkins |first=Will |date=January 14, 2014 |publisher=[[Art of the Title]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105191607/http://www.artofthetitle.com/title/true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"fc2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/3027343/a-behind-the-scenes-look-at-the-chilling-the-opening-credits-of-true-detective |title=A Behind-The-Scenes Look at the Chilling Opening Credits Of 'True Detective' |last=Rhodes |first=Margaret |date=March 7, 2014 |website=Fast Company |publisher=Fast Company, Inc. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105214628/http://www.fastcodesign.com/3027343/a-behind-the-scenes-look-at-the-chilling-the-opening-credits-of-true-detective |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> The design team emphasized southern Louisiana's industrial landscape because it reflected the characters' traits and personal, inner struggles. Clair stated that from the start he had an \"unusually clear\" vision of ''True Detective''{{'s}} finished opening sequence.<ref name=aott/> Using [[Richard Misrach]]'s photography book ''Petrochemical America'' (2012) as a template, the production team initially photographed the local scenery, and the resulting images were woven together to form the core of the title sequence.<ref name=fc2/> By the time production began animating, they faced several problems: the photographic stills were too grainy and the footage was too jagged. As a result, many shots were digitally altered and slowed to about a tenth of their original speed, which, according to Clair, \"evoked a surreal and floaty mood that perfectly captured what we were after.\"<ref name=aott/>\n\nCreation of a [[3D computer graphics|3D]] effect required the design team to use an assortment of [[low poly|low-poly meshes]], or 3D geometric models.<ref name=aott/> Using a variety of animation and special effects techniques, these images were later [[superimposed]] \"with painstaking care\" to avoid a sterile, digitized look.<ref name=fc2/> Clair said, \"The most crucial thing to me was that this didn't feel digital, so we went to great lengths to incorporate as much organic imagery as possible.\"<ref name=fc2/> For some stills, the design team created [[digital double]]s to develop more texture. The sequence's final cut was polished using optical glitching and [[motion blur|motion distortion]] techniques.<ref name=aott/> ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' included the opening sequence in a list of ten of the best title sequences on television.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/how-patrick-clair-won-the-emmy-for-90-seconds-of-true-detective-20140818-104xuz.html |title=How Patrick Clair won the Emmy for 90 seconds of True Detective |last=Kalina |first=Paul |date=August 22, 2014 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105215333/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/how-patrick-clair-won-the-emmy-for-90-seconds-of-true-detective-20140818-104xuz.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\nSeason one's opening theme is \"Far from Any Road\", an [[alternative country]] song originally composed by [[The Handsome Family]] for their 2003 album ''[[Singing Bones]]''.<ref name=fc2/> The ''True Detective'' soundtrack features a compilation of [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[blues]] music, which were selected by Pizzolatto and [[T Bone Burnett]]. The pair opposed the use of [[Cajun music]] and [[swamp blues]] for the season's musical score because they felt it was overdone.<ref name=mj/> Burnett said the score was intended to be character-driven, rather than inspired by other crime fiction drama.<ref name=\"mj\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/mixed-media/2014/01/t-bone-burnett-true-detective-hbo-music-songs |title=T Bone Burnett on How He Chooses Music for True Detective |last=Suebsaeng |first=Asawin |date=January 24, 2014 |website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |publisher=Foundation For National Progress |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105220121/https://www.motherjones.com/mixed-media/2014/01/t-bone-burnett-true-detective-hbo-music-songs |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Songs by [[Bo Diddley]], [[Melvins]], [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[The Staple Singers]], [[Grinderman]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Vashti Bunyan]], [[Townes Van Zandt]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a27608/true-detective-kurt-vonnegut/ |title=True Detective's Mystifying Kurt Vonnegut Connection |last=O'Neil |first=Luke |date=March 4, 2014 |website=Esquire |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105215854/http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a27608/true-detective-kurt-vonnegut/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> and [[Captain Beefheart]] appear in season one. Burnett also composed original pieces with [[Rhiannon Giddens]], who used a [[Swarmatron]] synthesizer, and [[Cassandra Wilson]].<ref name=\"mj\" /> HBO released an abridged soundtrack album, featuring 14 tracks from ''True Detective''{{'s}} first two seasons, on August 14, 2015, through physical media and [[iTunes]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/tv-film-news/true-detective-soundtrack-released-finally-6274097 |title=True Detective soundtrack released: FINALLY the hit TV show's magnificently moody music is available to buy |last=Allen |first=Gavin |date=August 18, 2015 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707204704/http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/tv-film-news/true-detective-soundtrack-released-finally-6274097 |archive-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Themes and analysis==\n===Masculinity and depiction of women===\n\nCommentators have noted [[masculinity]] as a theme in ''True Detective''. Christopher Lirette of ''[[Southern Spaces]]'' said the show was about \"men living in a brutally masculine world\" and women are depicted as \"things-to-be-saved and erotic obstacles\" \u00e0 la ''[[Double Indemnity (film)|Double Indemnity]]'' (1944) and ''[[Chinatown (1974 film)|Chinatown]]'' (1974).<ref name=sspaces/> ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''{{'s}} Willa Paskin said ''True Detective''{{'s}} depiction of its female characters\u2014as sex workers, the deceased and \"a nagging wife\"\u2014seemed to reveal an intent to reflect the protagonists' \"blinkered worldview and the very masculine, Southern cop culture they inhabited\".<ref name=\"slate2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/03/10/true_detective_has_a_woman_problem_yes_and_that_s_partly_why_people_love.html |title=True Detective Does Have a Woman Problem. That's Partly Why People Love It |last=Paskin |first=Willa |date=March 10, 2014 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |publisher=[[The Slate Group]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105220604/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/03/10/true_detective_has_a_woman_problem_yes_and_that_s_partly_why_people_love.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Some commentators saw Hart's characterization as a manifestation of this idea, evident through his conventional view of [[Madonna\u2013whore complex|women as virgins and whores]], as well as his treatment of Maggie and Audrey.<ref name=\"sspaces\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.southernspaces.org/2014/something-true-about-louisiana-hbos-true-detective-and-petrochemical-america-aesthetic |title=Something True about Louisiana: HBO's True Detective and the Petrochemical America Aesthetic |last=Lirette |first=Christopher |date=August 31, 2014 |website=[[Southern Spaces]] |publisher=[[Emory University]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106161348/http://southernspaces.org/2014/something-true-about-louisiana-hbos-true-detective-and-petrochemical-america-aesthetic |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"thinkp\">{{Cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/alyssa/2014/02/24/3322541/true-detective/ |title=Why Men Should Want 'True Detective' To Have Great, Nuanced Female Characters |last=Rosenberg |first=Alyssa |date=February 24, 2014 |publisher=[[Think Progress]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105221356/http://thinkprogress.org/alyssa/2014/02/24/3322541/true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"grant\">{{Cite web |url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/her-looming-shadow-grows-the-women-of-true-detective/ |title=Her Looming Shadow Grows: The Complex Women of True Detective |last=Lambert |first=Molly |date=February 24, 2014 |publisher=[[Grantland]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105221607/http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/her-looming-shadow-grows-the-women-of-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> When Hart confronts the two men who had sex with Audrey, he is in essence \"charging other men a price for infringing on the daughter he sees, in a muddled way, as both deserving of protection and badly in need of being controlled\".<ref name=thinkp/>\n\nIn her piece for ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'', Janet Turley said that the women \"become reflections of the men\", given that the ''True Detective'' universe is seen through the eyes of the show's male leads.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/03/09/true_detective_has_a_women_problem/ |title='True Detective' has a woman problem |last=Turley |first=Janet |date=March 9, 2014 |website=[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105222256/http://www.salon.com/2014/03/09/true_detective_has_a_women_problem/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Sam Adams of ''[[Indiewire]]'' contended that the story was about \"the horrible things men do to women\", many of which are never reported to or investigated by authorities. Adams wrote, \"No one missed Dora Lange. Marie Fontenot disappeared, and the police let a rumor stop them from following up\".<ref name=indie2/> He said the role of women was more profound because Cohle suffers through his ex-wife and deceased daughter and Hart is unable to \"deal appropriately with the women who are there\".<ref name=\"indie2\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/criticwire/true-detective-episode-6-review-haunted-houses-women |title=Female Bodies and the Philbrosophy of 'True Detective' |last=Adams |first=Sam |date=February 24, 2014 |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105223113/http://blogs.indiewire.com/criticwire/true-detective-episode-6-review-haunted-houses-women# |archive-date=November 5, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015}}</ref> According to Scott Wilson, a cultural studies lecturer at [[Kingston University]], women are categorised as \"the [[superego]]ic, the [[obscene]] and the [[sacred]]\".<ref name=Shipley160/> Maggie, in Wilson's interpretation, is portrayed as the superegoic wife who \"constantly makes demands on her guilty husband or partner tying him or her down and deflecting him or her from his symbolic role as police\".<ref name=\"Shipley160\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=160}}</ref> \n\nThe philosopher Erin K. Stapleton subscribes to the theory that Dora Lange's corpse serves to \"provide the initial territory or orientation through which the communities of ''True Detective'' are formed.\"<ref name=\"Shipley170\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=170}}</ref> It is through Dora's corpse that Cohle and Hart's partnership is first clearly articulated and in addition to their own bond, \"the intimate knowledge\" of her body is the basis of all of the other relationships in their respective lives.<ref name=Shipley170/><ref name=\"Shipley164\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=164}}</ref> Her narrative thus, by proxy, influences both men's character development as they delve into the case.<ref name=\"Shipley173\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=173}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n\n''True Detective'' explores Christianity and the dichotomy between religion and rationality. Born into a devout [[Catholic]] household, Pizzolatto said that as a child he saw religion as storytelling that acts \"as an escape from the truth\".<ref name=\"beast3\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/06/true-detective-s-godless-universe-is-the-hbo-show-anti-christian.html |title='True Detective's' Godless Universe: is the HBO Show Anti-Christian? |last=Romano |first=Andrew |date=March 6, 2014 |website=The Daily Beast |publisher=The Newsweek Daily Beast Company |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105223714/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/06/true-detective-s-godless-universe-is-the-hbo-show-anti-christian.html |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> According to Andrew Romano at ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', the season alludes to Pizzolatto's childhood and creates a parallel between Christianity and the supernatural theology of \"Carcosa\": \"Both&nbsp;...&nbsp;are stories. Stories people tell themselves to escape reality. Stories that 'violate every law of the universe.'\"<ref name=beast3/> Romano believed this message is not critical of religion ''per se''; rather it shows how the \"power of storytelling\" and religious zeal \"can wind [you] up in some pretty sick places.\"<ref name=beast3/> Jeff Jensen from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' has opined that the show becomes more self-aware through Cohle's harsh critiques of religion, which he viewed as a vehicle for commentary about pop culture escapism.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/01/12/true-detective-premiere |title='True Detective' post-mortem: Unraveling the mysteries |last=Jensen |first=Jeff |date=January 12, 2014 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105223958/http://www.ew.com/article/2014/01/12/true-detective-premiere |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Stapleton observed that the crimes on ''True Detective''\u2014through its victims and the implications of sacrifice and sexual violence\u2014\"respond to the conservative Christianity from which they originate, and seek to exploit the opportunities for the pleasure of transgression such a structure offers.\"<ref name=\"Shipley169\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=169}}</ref>\n\nTheorist Edia Connole saw connections to [[Philip Marlowe]] and ''[[Le Morte d'Arthur]]''{{'s}} [[Lancelot]] in ''True Detective''{{'s}} presentation of Cohle, all \"knights whose duty to their liege lord is tempered with devotion to God.\"<ref name=\"Shipley63\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=63}}</ref> Other aspects of ''True Detective'' evoke Christian imagery, including the opening scene, which Connole felt mirrored the [[crucifixion of Jesus]].<ref name=\"Shipley61\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=61}}</ref> The author and philosopher Finn Janning argued that Cohle's evolution illustrates an affinity between [[Buddhism]] and [[Pessimism#philosophical pessimism|philosophical pessimism]].<ref name=budd/> A self-proclaimed pessimist, Cohle is, however, changed by a [[near-death experience]] in the season finale, in which he has an epiphany, seeing death as \"pure love\": this echoes the Buddhist concept of [[rigpa]].<ref name=\"budd\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.philosophyoflife.org/jpl201408.pdf |title=True Detective: Pessimism, Buddhism, or Philosophy? |last=Janning |first=Finn |date=December 2014 |website=Journal of Philosophy of Life |format=PDF |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403024031/http://www.philosophyoflife.org/jpl201408.pdf |archive-date=April 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Philosophical pessimism and influences===\n[[File:Robert William Chambers.jpg|alt=A publicity portrait of Chambers, circa 1903|thumb|upright|Pizzolatto used Robert W. Chambers' (pictured) ''[[The King in Yellow]]'' as the backbone for much of the season's story.]]\n\nCritics have offered many readings of the influence of [[weird fiction|weird]] and [[horror fiction]] on ''True Detective''{{'s}} narrative, often examining the influence of [[Robert W. Chambers]]' short story collection ''[[The King in Yellow]]'' (1895) and [[Thomas Ligotti]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/02/02/writer-nic-pizzolatto-on-thomas-ligotti-and-the-weird-secrets-of-true-detective/ |title=Writer Nic Pizzolatto on Thomas Ligotti and the Weird Secrets of 'True Detective' |last=Calia |first=Michael |date=February 2, 2014 |website=The Wall Street Journal |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105224449/https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/02/02/writer-nic-pizzolatto-on-thomas-ligotti-and-the-weird-secrets-of-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Allusions to ''The King in Yellow'' can be observed in the show's dark philosophy,<ref name=\"wsj2\">{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/01/30/the-most-shocking-thing-about-hbos-true-detective/ |title=The Most Shocking Thing About HBO's 'True Detective' |last=Calia |first=Michael |date=January 30, 2014 |website=The Wall Street Journal |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105235314/https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/01/30/the-most-shocking-thing-about-hbos-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> its recurring use of \"Carcosa\" and \"The Yellow King\" as [[motif (narrative)|motifs]] throughout the series, and its symbolic use of yellow as a thematic signature that signifies insanity and decadence.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://io9.com/the-one-literary-reference-you-must-know-to-appreciate-1523076497 |title=The One Literary Reference You Must Know to Appreciate ''True Detective'' |last=Hughes |first=Michael M. |date=February 14, 2014 |publisher=[[io9]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105225049/http://io9.com/the-one-literary-reference-you-must-know-to-appreciate-1523076497 |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Pizzolatto was accused of plagiarizing Ligotti because of close similarities between lines in ''True Detective'' and text from Ligotti's nonfiction book ''The Conspiracy Against the Human Race'' (2010)\u2014accusations Pizzolatto denied, while acknowledging Ligotti's influence.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/08/showbiz/tv/true-detective-pizzolatto-plagiarism/ |title='True Detective' writer accused of plagiarism |last=Leopoldo |first=Todd |date=August 8, 2014 |publisher=[[CNN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513043118/http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/08/showbiz/tv/true-detective-pizzolatto-plagiarism/ |archive-date=May 13, 2016}}</ref> \n\nOther philosophers and writers identified as influences include [[Arthur Schopenhauer]],<ref name=wsj2/> [[Friedrich Nietzsche]],<ref name=cnn/> [[Gilles Deleuze]],<ref name=\"budd\" /> [[Ray Brassier]], [[Emil Cioran]], and [[Eugene Thacker]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/lincolnmichel/a-true-detective-reading-list |title=A 'True Detective' Reading List |last=Michel |first=Lincoln |date=February 18, 2014 |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105235603/http://www.buzzfeed.com/lincolnmichel/a-true-detective-reading-list |archive-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Mathijs Peters, in a piece for ''[[Film International]]'', argued that ''True Detective'' probes Schopenhauerian philosophy through its approach to individuality, self-denial, the battle between dark and light.<ref name=\"Filmint\">{{Cite web |url=http://filmint.nu/?p=14036 |title='A Giant Gutter in Outer Space': On the Schopenhauerian Themes of HBO's hit series True Detective |last=Peters |first=Mathijs |date=2014 |website=[[Film International]] |publisher=Intellect Ltd. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925003024/http://filmint.nu/?p=14036 |archive-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> Ben Woodard noted the show's evolving philosophy, which examines a setting where culture, religion and society are the consequences of biological weakness. Woodward wrote, \"Biological programming gets recuperated and socially redistributed visions, faiths, and acerbic personalities take the reins of uncertain ends creating a world where 'people go away'.\"<ref name=\"Shipley110\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=110}}</ref> Even the setting, Fintan Neylan argued, emphasizes a world \"where the decrepitude of human ordering cannot be hidden\".<ref name=\"Shipley81\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=81}}</ref> \"This is not a place where hope fled; it is a place where hope could never take root. It is with these people and environs that the real horror is sourced\".<ref name=Shipley81/> Neylan observed that Cohle's actions are not motivated by [[misanthropy]], rather a drive to challenge \"those who try to either disguise or manipulate this frailty of humans for their own benefit\".<ref name=\"Shipley82\">{{harvnb|Shipley|2014|p=82}}</ref> Cohle ultimately confronts \"an entire philosophical history which has taken its task as that of sweeping frailty away\".<ref name=Shipley82/> [[Christopher Orr (film critic)|Christopher Orr]] at ''The Atlantic'' said ''True Detective'' was \"[[David Fincher|Fincherian]] in the best sense\", a fusion of ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Se7en]]'' (1995) and ''[[Zodiac (film)|Zodiac]]'' (2007), because of its subject matter, sleek cinematography and \"vivid, unsettling\" aura.<ref name=\"atlantic2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/02/-em-true-detective-em-the-best-show-on-tv/283727/ |title=''True Detective'': The Best Show on TV |last=Orr |first=Christopher |date=February 11, 2014 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |publisher=Hayley Romer |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106155900/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/02/-em-true-detective-em-the-best-show-on-tv/283727/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators noted further influences from comic book literature. Adams likened Cohle to the protagonist of ''[[Alan Moore's The Courtyard]]'' and drew parallels with [[Grant Morrison]]'s ''[[The Invisibles]]'' for the show's brief exploration of [[M-theory]] with one of Cohle's monologues.<ref name=\"comicindiewire\">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/criticwire/the-comic-books-behind-true-detective |title=The Comic Books Behind 'True Detective' |last=Adams |first=Sam |date=February 21, 2014 |publisher=Indiewire |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105235908/http://blogs.indiewire.com/criticwire/the-comic-books-behind-true-detective# |archive-date=November 5, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015}}</ref> [[ComicsAlliance]] and ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' columnist Abraham Riesman cited ''[[Top 10 (comics)|Top 10]]'' as the inspiration for the season finale based on dialogue from the episode's closing scene.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-finale-comics-alan-moore-homage.html |title=Was There a Hidden Comic Book Homage in the True Detective Finale? |last=Riesman |first=Abraham |date=March 10, 2014 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |publisher=New York Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106000129/http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/true-detective-finale-comics-alan-moore-homage.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://comicsalliance.com/true-detective-comic-books-weird-fiction-secrets-influences-alan-moore-grant-morrison-invisibles-hbo |title=The Expert's Guide To HBO's 'True Detective' And Weird Comic Book Fiction |last=Stewart |first=Adam and Mark |date=April 4, 2014 |publisher=[[ComicsAlliance]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106001143/http://comicsalliance.com/true-detective-comic-books-weird-fiction-secrets-influences-alan-moore-grant-morrison-invisibles-hbo/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Auteurism===\n\nAnother principal topic of discussion among critics has been ''True Detective''{{'s}} [[auteur theory|auteurist]] sensibility. Auteurism (from French ''[[:wikt:auteur#French|auteur]]'') is a critical framework that assesses films or other works of art as reflections of the personal vision of individual authors, typically a director or writer.<ref name=time2/> At the helm of each of the season's episodes are Pizzolatto and Fukunaga\u2014its sole writer and director\u2014a partnership that provides the show a unique place in a traditionally collaborative medium where broad sets of writers and directors work in tandem.<ref name=\"time2\">{{Cite web |url=http://time.com/3990805/true-detective-finale-louie-tv-auteurs/ |title=True Detective, Louie, and the Limits of TV Auteurism |last=Poniewozik |first=James |date=August 10, 2015 |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804035430/http://time.com/3990805/true-detective-finale-louie-tv-auteurs/ |archive-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"thelist\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/60066-mad-men-true-detective-and-the-rise-of-the-tv-auteur/ |title=Mad Men, True Detective and the rise of the TV auteur |last=Robertson |first=Colin |date=April 9, 2014 |website=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925222238/https://www.list.co.uk/article/60066-mad-men-true-detective-and-the-rise-of-the-tv-auteur/ |archive-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> Colin Robertson at ''[[The List (magazine)|The List]]'' saw ''Twin Peaks'' as the most notable artistic antecedent to ''True Detective''{{'s}} first season, seeing that both shows challenge crime drama cliches and \"use the genre conventions of a whodunnit-style mystery as a sublimely subversive diving board, and leap off from there to tell a broader story.\"<ref name=thelist/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Viewership===\n''True Detective'' debuted to 2.3 million U.S. viewers, becoming HBO's highest rated series premiere since the [[Boardwalk Empire (episode)|pilot episode]] of ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/01/true-detective-girls-hbo-ratings.html |title='True Detective': HBO's Best Premiere Since 2010 |last=Adalian |first=Josef |date=January 13, 2014 |website=New York |publisher=New York Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106134441/http://www.vulture.com/2014/01/true-detective-girls-hbo-ratings.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Ratings remained steady and peaked at the finale, which drew 3.5 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/10/entertainment/la-et-ct-hbo-true-detective-finale-ratings-20140310 |title=HBO's 'True Detective' season finale locks up a ratings high |last=Faughnder |first=Ryan |date=March 10, 2014 |website=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Timothy Ryan |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106141123/http://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/10/entertainment/la-et-ct-hbo-true-detective-finale-ratings-20140310 |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Overall, season one averaged 2.33 million viewers,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/true-detective-season-one-ratings-31235/ |title='True Detective': Season One Ratings |date=March 12, 2014 |publisher=TV Series Finale |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/20141202124329/http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/true-detective-season-one-ratings-31235/ |archive-date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> and its average gross audience (which includes [[digital video recorder|DVR]] recordings, reruns, and [[HBO Go]] streaming) totaled 11.9 million viewers per episode, thus becoming HBO's highest rated freshman show since the first season of ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' 13 years earlier.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/04/true-detective-now-most-watched-hbo-freshman-series-ever-715055/ |title='True Detective' Now Most Watched HBO Freshman Series Ever |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=April 15, 2014 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106142115/http://deadline.com/2014/04/true-detective-now-most-watched-hbo-freshman-series-ever-715055/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ratings-true-detective-soars-with-finale.html |title=Ratings: True Detective Soars With Finale |last=Adalian |first=Josef |date=March 10, 2014 |website=New York |publisher=New York Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106212246/http://www.vulture.com/2014/03/ratings-true-detective-soars-with-finale.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |width=195px |align=right | quote = ''True Detective'', coming as it does after what was arguably the best year for dramas in at least five years ... just puts an exclamation point on the topic of excessive quality. | source =&ndash; '''Tim Goodman, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'''''.<ref name=\"thr2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/hbos-true-detective-starring-matthew-668182 |title=True Detective: TV Review |last=Goodman |first=Tim |date=January 2, 2014 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106154840/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/hbos-true-detective-starring-matthew-668182 |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>}}\nThe American press considered ''True Detective'' to be among the best television shows of 2014.<ref name=\"best2014\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/tv-critics-pick-10-best-tv-shows-of-2014 |title=TV Critic Top 10 Lists \u2013 Best TV Shows of 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106015332/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/tv-critics-pick-10-best-tv-shows-of-2014 |archive-date=November 6, 2015 |publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> Many critics complimented the work of both lead actors,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wiegand |first=David |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/True-Detective-review-2-stars-shine-brightly-5129041.php |title='True Detective' review: 2 stars shine brightly |date=January 9, 2014 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160139/http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/True-Detective-review-2-stars-shine-brightly-5129041.php |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st--true-detective-review-20140110-story.html |title=Review: 'True Detective's' slow and steady pace a winning formula |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=January 10, 2014 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160336/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st--true-detective-review-20140110-story.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> often singling out McConaughey for further praise,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Poniewozik |first=James |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/09/dead-tree-alert-hbos-existential-detective-story/ |title=Dead Tree Alert: HBO\u2019s Existential Detective Story |date=January 9, 2014 |work=Time |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804040018/http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/09/dead-tree-alert-hbos-existential-detective-story/ |archive-date=August 4, 2017 |issn=0040-781X}}</ref><ref name=\"vfreview\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> with his work described as \"jaw-droppingly great\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url=http://uproxx.com/sepinwall/review-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-amaze-in-hbos-true-detective/ |title=Review: McConaughey & Harrelson amaze in HBO\u2019s \u2018True Detective\u2019 |date=January 7, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524144416/http://uproxx.com/sepinwall/review-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-amaze-in-hbos-true-detective/ |archive-date=May 24, 2017 |publisher=[[Uproxx]]}}</ref> and \"simply magnetic\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.redeyechicago.com/entertainment/tv/redeye-true-detective-tv-review-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-mesmerize-20140109-story.html |title=TV review: 'True Detective' mesmerizes |last=Wagner |first=Curt |date=January 9, 2014 |website=[[RedEye]] |publisher=[[Amy Guth]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106161009/http://www.redeyechicago.com/entertainment/tv/redeye-true-detective-tv-review-matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-mesmerize-20140109-story.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>  Some reviewers singled out simple conversational scenes, often in claustrophobic interiors, as some of the best acting in the series.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/hbos-true-detective-a-murky-mystery-bogged-down-in-a-swamp/2014/01/09/1899e634-771d-11e3-8963-b4b654bcc9b2_story.html |title=HBO's 'True Detective': A murky mystery, bogged down in a swamp |last=Stuever |first=Hank |date=January 9, 2014 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |publisher=[[Katharine Weymouth]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804035956/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/hbos-true-detective-a-murky-mystery-bogged-down-in-a-swamp/2014/01/09/1899e634-771d-11e3-8963-b4b654bcc9b2_story.html |archive-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/true-detective-avoids-pulp-in-favor-of-philosophy-200791 |title=True Detective avoids pulps in favor of philosophy |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |date=January 10, 2014 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=The Onion, Inc. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160548/http://www.avclub.com/review/true-detective-avoids-pulp-in-favor-of-philosophy-200791 |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/true-detective-review_b_4569442.html |title='True Detective' Review: McConaughey And Harrelson Are Terrific In New Crime Drama |last=Ryan |first=Maureen |date=January 9, 2014 |website=The Huffington Post}}</ref> The characterization received mixed reviews: Cohle's speeches, described by ''[[HuffPost]]'' as \"mesmerizing monologues\",<ref name=\":1\" /> and by ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' as dense and interesting material,<ref name=\"vfreview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/01/true-detective-review-hbo |title=Review: HBO's True Detective Is Mind Over Murder' |last=Lawson |first=Richard |date=January 15, 2014 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106155611/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/01/true-detective-review-hbo |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> were criticized by the ''[[New York Post]]'' as \"'70s-era psycho-babble\" which slowed down the story.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/01/07/true-detective-needs-dramatic-jolt/l |title='True Detective' needs dramatic jolt |last=Starr |first=Michael |date=January 7, 2014 |website=[[New York Post]] |publisher=Jesse Angelo |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106174952/http://nypost.com/2014/01/07/true-detective-needs-dramatic-jolt/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>  Several critics viewed the portrayals of women as stereotypical: \"either angry or aroused\",<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=http://grantland.com/features/matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-hbo-true-detective/ |title=Resisting Arrest |last=Greenwald |first=Andy |date=January 8, 2014 |website=[[Grantland]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106214125/http://grantland.com/features/matthew-mcconaughey-woody-harrelson-hbo-true-detective/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/television/2014/03/03/140303crte_television_nussbaum |title=The shallow deep talk of 'True Detective' |last=Nussbaum |first=Emily |date=March 3, 2014 |website=[[The New Yorker]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106162401/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/03/03/cool-story-bro |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> though Michelle Monaghan was praised for her performance in a \"thankless role\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nPizzolatto and Fukunaga, as sole writer and director of the entire series, were able to exercise much stronger control over the show than is usual for a TV series, which let the show take risks: the pacing, dialogue, and cinematography all departed at times from the expectations for a television drama.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/southern-discomfort--is-true-detective-starring-woody-harrelson-and-matthew-mcconaughey-the-best-us-detective-show-since-the-wire-9136919.html |title=Is True Detective, starring Woody Harrelson and Matthew McConaughey, the best US detective show since The Wire? |last=Hughes |first=Sarah |date=February 18, 2014 |website=[[The Independent]] |publisher=Independent Print Limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160740/http://variety.com/2014/tv/reviews/tv-review-hbos-true-detective-1201024636/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>  Pizzolatto's scripts drew occasional criticism as \"self-consciously literary\" and overwritten,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://artsfuse.org/98478/fuse-tv-review-hbos-true-detective-a-work-in-progress/ |title=Fuse TV Review: HBO's 'True Detective'\u2014A Work in Progress |last=Peary |first=Gerald |date=January 8, 2014 |website=[[The Arts Fuse]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106175757/http://artsfuse.org/98478/fuse-tv-review-hbos-true-detective-a-work-in-progress/ |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> and several journalists attributed mistakes in the script to Pizzolatto's inexperience in writing TV drama.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/11/arts/television/mcconaughey-and-harrelson-star-in-true-detective-on-hbo.html |title=A Coupling as Bizarre as the Murder |last=Hale |first=Mike |date=January 11, 2014 |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106161212/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/11/arts/television/mcconaughey-and-harrelson-star-in-true-detective-on-hbo.html?_r=0 |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Despite the criticism, the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' and [[Uproxx]] described the season as \"ambitious\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10654871/True-Detective-Sky-Atlantic-review-a-work-of-depth-and-cinematic-flair.html |title=True Detective, Sky Atlantic, review: a work of depth and cinematic flair |last=Harvey |first=Chris |date=February 22, 2014 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106155244/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10654871/True-Detective-Sky-Atlantic-review-a-work-of-depth-and-cinematic-flair.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> and \"dense with event and meaning\".<ref name=\":3\" /> The flashback structure also divided critics: it was described as \"impressively seamless\",<ref name=\":6\" /> and \"a major asset\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2014/feb/27/true-detective-season-one-episode-one-long-bright-dark |title=True Detective recap: season one, episode one \u2013 The Long Bright Dark |last=Mumford |first=Gwilym |date=February 27, 2014 |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160921/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2014/feb/27/true-detective-season-one-episode-one-long-bright-dark |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> but the fragmented approach to storytelling was considered a flaw by others.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=vfreview/> Uproxx praised Fukunaga's atmospheric and \"hauntingly beautiful\" cinematography,<ref name=\":3\" /> and ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' complimented the \"spare, hollow, percussive\" soundtrack,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/television/2014/01/09/mcconaughey-and-harrelson-make-true-detective-arresting/9FuWBQeEZZpfxGqaE3KaeJ/story.html |title=McConaughey, Harrelson make 'True Detective' arresting |last=Rodman |first=Sarah |date=January 9, 2014 |website=[[Boston Globe]] |publisher=[[John W. Henry]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160503/http://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/television/2014/01/09/mcconaughey-and-harrelson-make-true-detective-arresting/9FuWBQeEZZpfxGqaE3KaeJ/story.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> with Uproxx crediting the creative control the two men wielded for the quality of the result.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe story of two mismatched detectives working on a case was described by several critics as a clich\u00e9,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/11/true-detective-review-you-have-to-watch-hbo-s-revolutionary-crime-classic.html |title='True Detective' Review: You Have to Watch HBO's Revolutionary Crime Classic |last=Romano |first=Andrew |date=January 11, 2014 |website=The Daily Beast |publisher=The Newsweek Daily Beast Company |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510214925/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/11/true-detective-review-you-have-to-watch-hbo-s-revolutionary-crime-classic.html |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" /> though many reviewers felt this was made into a strength: ''The Daily Beast'', for example, described the narrative as having \"the potential to be revolutionary\",<ref name=\":7\" /> and the [[Grantland]] reviewer felt that \"the form is truly radical and forward-thinking\", though he added that \"the content is anything but\".<ref name=\":2\" />  Emily Nussbaum, writing for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', was also critical, considering the real story to be \"a simpler tale: one about heroic male outlines and closeups of female asses\"; she described the philosophical monologues as \"dorm room deep talk\" and argued that the show had \"fallen for its own sales pitch\".<ref name=\":8\" /> Other reviewers were more positive: comments ranged from \"as frighteningly nervy and furious in its delivery and intent as prime David Lynch\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/review/true-detective-season-one |title=True Detective: Season One |last=Cabin |first=Chris |date=January 8, 2014 |website=[[Slant Magazine]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106161230/http://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/review/true-detective-season-one |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> to \"one of the most riveting and provocative series I've ever seen\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by True Detective}}\n[[File:Woody Harrelson and Matthew McConaughey at the 66th Primetime Emmy Awards.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=A photograph of Woody Harrelson and Matthew McConaughey at the 66th Primetime Emmy Awards|Harrelson (left) and McConaughey (right) at the 66th Primetime Emmy Awards.]]\n\nAs the nominations for the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] approached, early media reports named ''True Detective'' among several potential miniseries candidates, due to a revision made by the [[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] that recognized film and miniseries content as distinct categories.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-rules-change-restores-movie-and-miniseries-split-1201114252/ |title=Emmy Rules Change Restores Movie and Miniseries Split |last=Lowry |first=Brian |date=February 20, 2014 |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510201216/http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-rules-change-restores-movie-and-miniseries-split-1201114252/ |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> By March 2014, HBO had submitted ''True Detective'' as a drama series contender,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/true-detective-to-submit-as-drama-series-not-miniseries-for-emmys-1201146631/ |title=True Detective' to Submit as Drama Series, Not Miniseries, for Emmys |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=March 25, 2014 |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510203116/http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/true-detective-to-submit-as-drama-series-not-miniseries-for-emmys-1201146631/ |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/television/emmys-shocker-hbo-to-submit-true-detective-as-best-drama-series-not-miniseries |title=Emmys Shocker: HBO to Submit 'True Detective' as Best Drama Series, Not Miniseries |last=Travers |first=Ben |date=March 25, 2014 |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510203303/http://www.indiewire.com/article/television/emmys-shocker-hbo-to-submit-true-detective-as-best-drama-series-not-miniseries |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/tv/la-et-st-en-gold-standard-20140515-story.html |title=Gold Standard Emmy bids by 'True Detective' and 'Fargo' bend categories |last=Whipp |first=Glenn |date=May 15, 2014 |website=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Timothy Ryan |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106160336/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st--true-detective-review-20140110-story.html |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref> an unconventional move given the show's anthology format and fierce competition from the likes of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' and ''[[House of Cards (U.S. series)|House of Cards]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emmys-hbos-true-detective-compete-684153 |title=Emmys: HBO's 'True Detective' to Compete in Fierce Drama Series Category |last=Hunt |first=Stacey |date=March 25, 2014 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510210136/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/tv/la-et-st-en-gold-standard-20140515-story.html |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> HBO's decision was censured by [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] president [[John Landgraf]], who remarked to reporters at a press event: \"My own personal point of view is that a miniseries is a story that ends, a series is a story that continues. To tell you the truth, I think it's actually unfair for HBO to put ''True Detective'' in the drama series category because essentially you can get certain actors to do a closed-ended series \u2013 a la [[Billy Bob Thornton]] in ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]'' or Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson in ''True Detective'' \u2013 who you can't get to sign on for a seven-year [regular drama series] deal.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/04/09/fx-hbo-true-detective-emmy-unfair |title=Unfair' HBO knocked for 'True Detective' Emmy bid |last=Hibbert |first=James |date=April 9, 2014 |website=Entertainment Weekly |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510212024/http://www.ew.com/article/2014/04/09/fx-hbo-true-detective-emmy-unfair |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, ''True Detective'' emerged as a frontrunner heading into the Primetime Emmy season, and in July 2014, was nominated for twelve awards; its closest rival, ''Breaking Bad'', received sixteen nominations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/07/emmys-analysis-true-detective-orange-is-the-new-black-broadcast-decline-801826/ |title=Emmy Noms Analysis: 'True Detective', 'Orange' & 'Shameless' Fare Well Amid Category Brouhaha As Free-TV Slips To New Low |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=July 10, 2014 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510214501/http://deadline.com/2014/07/emmys-analysis-true-detective-orange-is-the-new-black-broadcast-decline-801826/ |archive-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> The series ultimately won five Emmy awards: [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing]] (Fukunaga), Outstanding Casting, Outstanding Main Title Design, Outstanding Make-Up, and Outstanding Cinematography.<ref name=Emmys/> \n\n''True Detective'' was a candidate for a variety of awards, most of which recognized outstanding achievement in direction, cinematography, writing, and acting. It received four [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nominations, among them for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film|Best Miniseries or Television Film]], and a [[TCA Award]] for [[TCA Award for Program of the Year|Program of the Year]].<ref name=gg/><ref name=tca/> Among the show's wins include a [[British Academy Television Award]] (BAFTA) for [[British Academy Television Award for Best International Programme|Best International Programme]], a [[Writers Guild of America Award]] in the [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Dramatic Series|Dramatic Series]] category, and a [[Critics' Choice Television Award]] for [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Drama Series|Best Actor in a Drama Series]] (McConaughey).<ref name=bafta/><ref name=ccta/><ref name=wgaa/>\n{{-}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"| [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]]\n| ''True Detective''\n| {{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"12\"|<ref name=\"Emmys\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/true-detective |title=True Detective \u2013 Awards & Nominations |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106162816/http://www.emmys.com/shows/true-detective |archive-date=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Matthew McConaughey]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Woody Harrelson]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series]]\n| [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series]]\n| [[Nic Pizzolato]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\"|[[66th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Composition for a Series|Outstanding Music Composition for a Series]]\n| [[T Bone Burnett]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Casting for a Drama Series|Outstanding Casting for a Drama Series]]\n| Alexa L. Fogel, Christine Kromer and Meagan Lewis\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Make-up for a Single-C