y}}|caps=4|club=[[Scarlets]]|clubnat=Wales}}\n{{nat rs player|pos=WG|name=[[Aled Brew]]|age={{Birth date and age2|2011|9|9|1986|8|9|df=y}}|caps=7|club=[[Dragons (rugby union)|Newport Gwent Dragons]]|clubnat=Wales}}\n{{nat rs player|pos=WG|name=[[George North]]|age={{Birth date and age2|2011|9|9|1992|4|13|df=y}}|caps=8|club=[[Scarlets]]|clubnat=Wales}}\n{{nat rs player|pos=WG|name=[[Shane Williams]]|age={{Birth date and age2|2011|9|9|1977|2|26|df=y}}|caps=81|club=[[Ospreys (rugby union)|Ospreys]]|clubnat=Wales}}\n{{nat rs player|pos=FB|name=[[Lee Byrne]]|age={{Birth date and age2|2011|9|9|1980|6|1|df=y}}|caps=44|club=[[ASM Clermont Auvergne|Clermont]]|clubnat=France}}\n{{nat rs player|pos=FB|name=[[Leigh Halfpenny]]|age={{Birth date and age2|2011|9|9|1988|12|22|df=y}}|caps=20|club=[[Cardiff Blues]]|clubnat=Wales}}\n{{nat rs end}}\n\n==Player statistics==\n\n===Player representation by club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Players!!Clubs\n|-\n|14||{{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]], {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VVA-Podmoskovye Monino|VVA-Podmoskovye]]\n|-\n|13||{{flagicon|FRA}} [[ASM Clermont Auvergne|Clermont]], {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Stade Toulousain|Toulouse]]\n|-\n|12||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Benetton Rugby|Benetton Treviso]], {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Crusaders (rugby union)|Crusaders]], {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Montpellier H\u00e9rault RC|Montpellier]]\n|-\n|11||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Leicester Tigers]], {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ospreys (rugby union)|Ospreys]]\n|-\n|10||{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Suntory Sungoliath]], {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Aironi]], {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Queensland Reds|Reds]], {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Sale Sharks]], {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Scarlets]], {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Stade Fran\u00e7ais]]\n|}\n\n===Player representation by league===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!League!!Players||Percent||Outside <br> national <br> squad\n|-\n|Total||600|| ||\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|France}} [[Rugby union in France|France]]||126||21%||96\n|-\n|align=left|[[Pro14|Celtic League]]||105||18%||13\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|England}} [[English rugby union system|England]]||81||14%||55\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Rugby union in New Zealand|New Zealand]]||48||8%||18\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Rugby union in Japan|Japan]]||36||6%||7\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Rugby union in Australia|Australia]]||35||6%||5\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|South Africa}} [[Rugby union in South Africa|South Africa]]||35||6%||8\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|Romania}} [[Rugby union in Romania|Romania]]||22||4%||2\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Rugby union in Russia|Russia]]||22||4%||\u2014\n|-\n|align=left|Others||90||15%||\n|}\n\n===Average age of squads===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Average age!!Countries\n|-\n|26||[[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]], [[United States national rugby union team|United States]], [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]\n|-\n|27||[[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]], [[Fiji national rugby union team|Fiji]], [[Georgia national rugby union team|Georgia]], [[Namibia national rugby union team|Namibia]], [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]]\n|-\n|28||[[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]], [[England national rugby union team|England]], [[France national rugby union team|France]], [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]], [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]], [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]], [[Romania national rugby union team|Romania]], [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]], [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]], [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]], [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]]\n|-\n|29||[[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]]\n|}\n\nTaylor Paris of [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]] was the youngest player named to a squad at 18, while [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]]'s Viacheslav Grachev, 38, was the oldest. However, Paris did not appear in any of Canada's matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/statsguru/rugby/player/128737.html?class=1;template=results;type=player;view=match |title=Statsguru / Player analysis / Taylor Paris / Test matches |work=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=21 October 2011 }}</ref> making Wales' 19-year-old [[George North]] the youngest to actually appear in the World Cup.\n\n===Coaches representation by country===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Number!!Country!!Coaches\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|6||{{flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand||[[Kieran Crowley]], [[Robbie Deans]], [[Warren Gatland]], [[Graham Henry]], [[John Kirwan (rugby)|John Kirwan]], [[Isitolo Maka]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2||{{flagicon|ENG}} England||[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]], [[Andy Robinson]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} Ireland||[[Declan Kidney]], [[Eddie O'Sullivan]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|RSA}} South Africa||[[Peter de Villiers]], [[Nick Mallett]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1||8 countries||\n|}\n\n===Squad caps===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Pos.!!Caps!!Country!!Most capped player\n|-\n|1||1224||{{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]]||[[Victor Matfield]] (107)\n|-\n|2||1139||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]]||[[Mils Muliaina]] (98), [[Richie McCaw]] (100)\n|-\n|3||1068||{{flagicon|IRE|rugby union}} [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]]||[[Brian O'Driscoll]] (113)\n|-\n|4||1038||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]||[[Chris Paterson]] (105)\n|-\n|5||1036||{{flagicon|GEO}} [[Georgia national rugby union team|Georgia]]||[[Irakli Abuseridze]] (72)\n|-\n|6||1011||{{flagicon|FRA}} [[France national rugby union team|France]]||[[Damien Traille]] (83)\n|-\n|7||1008||{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]]||[[Andrea Lo Cicero]] (88)\n|-\n|8||896||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[England national rugby union team|England]]||[[Jonny Wilkinson]] (86)\n|-\n|9||865||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]]||[[Stephen Jones (rugby player)|Stephen Jones]] (100)\n|-\n|10||863||{{flagicon|ROM}} [[Romania national rugby union team|Romania]]||[[Cristian Petre]] (77)\n|-\n|11||820||{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]]||[[Alexander Khrokin]] (67)\n|-\n|12||811||{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]]||[[Nathan Sharpe]] (95)\n|-\n|13||685||{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]]||[[Hirotoki Onozawa]] (64)\n|-\n|14||582||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Argentina national rugby union team|Argentina]]||[[Mario Ledesma]] (78)\n|-\n|15||475||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]]||[[Ed Fairhurst]] (49)\n|-\n|16||444||{{flagicon|USA}} [[United States national rugby union team|United States]]||[[Mike MacDonald (rugby union)|Mike MacDonald]] (62)\n|-\n|17||408||{{flagicon|FIJ}} [[Fiji national rugby union team|Fiji]]||[[Nicky Little]] (67)\n|-\n|18||397||{{flagicon|SAM}} [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]]||[[Mahonri Schwalger]] (36)\n|-\n|19||366||{{flagicon|NAM}} [[Namibia national rugby union team|Namibia]]||[[Hugo Horn]] (31)\n|-\n|20||300||{{flagicon|TON}} [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]]||[[Aleki Lutui]], [[Ephraim Taukafa]] (30)\n|}\n\n[[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] had the most capped side in the World Cup with 1,224 caps. The most-capped player at the tournament was [[Brian O'Driscoll]] of [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], who entered the event with 113 caps for Ireland (not counting his appearances with the [[British and Irish Lions]]). Second on this list was his teammate [[Ronan O'Gara]] with 111.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2011 Rugby World Cup}}\n{{Rugby Union World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2011 Rugby World Cup Squads}}\n[[Category:2011 Rugby World Cup|Squads]]\n[[Category:Rugby World Cup squads]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix sporting links (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_Rugby_World_Cup_squads"}
{"title_page": "Johnny Gregory (bandleader)", "text_new": "'''Johnny Gregory'''  (born John Gregori, 12 October 1924<ref>[https://www.spaceagepop.com/gregory.htm Space Age Musicmaker: Johnny Gregory]</ref> or 1928<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ipnrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=johnny+gregory+1928+chaquito&source=bl&ots=Ztf35FvW6I&sig=ACfU3U27CrRmuUHSrpVLkAuBIbPKvRVABA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjP7pvviozoAhXUa8AKHf4uDSkQ6AEwCHoECB0QAQ#v=onepage&q=johnny%20gregory%201928%20chaquito&f=false Conductors and Composers of Popular Orchestral Music: A Biographical and Discographical Sourcebook, pg. 117]</ref>) was a British bandleader who also recorded as '''Chaquito'''.<ref>Collins Complete UK Hit Singles 1952-2004 - Page 370 Graham Betts - 2004 \"Initially known as an \u2026 UK orchestra leader Johnny Gregory also recorded as Chaquito.</ref><ref>The Guinness encyclopedia of popular music - Volume 3 - Page 1750 Colin Larkin - 1995   It's That Chaquito Again (1960), This Chaquito (1968), Thriller Themes (1972); with the Johnny Gregory Orchestra TV ...</ref><ref>Gramophone - Volume 49 - Page 1438 1972 \"LATIN AMERICAN The distinguished recording career spanning fourteen years of Chaquito is well portrayed by \"The ... LPs compiled from the albums made by this excellent band under the direction of arranger Johnny Gregory since 1958.</ref><ref>The Gramophone - Volume 50 - Page 256 1972 -</ref><ref>The latest LP from Chaquito, \"TV Thrillers\" (Philips 6308 087), is as disappointing as its predecessor \"Chaquito Magic\", but for a different reason. In his quest for something new for this excellent band's attention, Johnny Gregory has certainly ...</ref> He scored several film and TV shows, including ''[[Serena (1962 film)|Serena]]'' (1962), ''[[Impact (1963 film)|Impact]]'' (1963), ''[[Night Caller from Outer Space|The Night Caller]]'' (1965) and ''[[Don't Drink the Water (TV series)|Don't Drink the Water]]'' (1974).<ref>http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba00297c3</ref> He won an Ivor Novello Award in 1976 for \"Introduction and Air to a Stained Glass Window\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk/index.php/legends/johnny-gregory|title=A PORTRAIT OF JOHNNY GREGORY|last=JOHNSON|first=Bill|date=27 May 2004|website=www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> From 1974 to 1991 he was the conductor of the BBC Radio Orchestra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk/index.php/legends/johnny-gregory|title=A PORTRAIT OF JOHNNY GREGORY|last=JOHNSON|first=BILL|date=27 May 2004|website=www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>He composed his last film score in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk/index.php/legends/johnny-gregory|title=A PORTRAIT OF JOHNNY GREGORY|last=JOHNSON|first=Bill|date=27 May 2004|website=www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0339853}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gregory, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1920s births]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n[[Category:British bandleaders]]\n[[Category:British male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Easy listening musicians]]\n[[Category:English film score composers]]\n[[Category:English music arrangers]]\n[[Category:English television composers]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n\n{{UK-conductor-stub}}\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "'''Johnny Gregory'''  (born John Gregori, 12 October 1924<ref>[https://www.spaceagepop.com/gregory.htm Space Age Musicmaker: Johnny Gregory]</ref> or 1928<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ipnrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=johnny+gregory+1928+chaquito&source=bl&ots=Ztf35FvW6I&sig=ACfU3U27CrRmuUHSrpVLkAuBIbPKvRVABA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjP7pvviozoAhXUa8AKHf4uDSkQ6AEwCHoECB0QAQ#v=onepage&q=johnny%20gregory%201928%20chaquito&f=false Conductors and Composers of Popular Orchestral Music: A Biographical and Discographical Sourcebook, pg. 117]</ref>) was a British bandleader who also recorded as '''Chaquito'''.<ref>Collins Complete UK Hit Singles 1952-2004 - Page 370 Graham Betts - 2004 \"Initially known as an \u2026 UK orchestra leader Johnny Gregory also recorded as Chaquito.</ref><ref>The Guinness encyclopedia of popular music - Volume 3 - Page 1750 Colin Larkin - 1995   It's That Chaquito Again (1960), This Chaquito (1968), Thriller Themes (1972); with the Johnny Gregory Orchestra TV ...</ref><ref>Gramophone - Volume 49 - Page 1438 1972 \"LATIN AMERICAN The distinguished recording career spanning fourteen years of Chaquito is well portrayed by \"The ... LPs compiled from the albums made by this excellent band under the direction of arranger Johnny Gregory since 1958.</ref><ref>The Gramophone - Volume 50 - Page 256 1972 -</ref><ref>The latest LP from Chaquito, \"TV Thrillers\" (Philips 6308 087), is as disappointing as its predecessor \"Chaquito Magic\", but for a different reason. In his quest for something new for this excellent band's attention, Johnny Gregory has certainly ...</ref> He scored several film and TV shows, including ''[[Serena (1962 film)|Serena]]'' (1962), ''[[Impact (1963 film)|Impact]]'' (1963), ''[[Night Caller from Outer Space|The Night Caller]]'' (1965) and ''[[Don't Drink the Water (TV series)|Don't Drink the Water]]'' (1974).<ref>http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba00297c3</ref> He won an Ivor Novello Award in 1976 for \"Introduction and Air to a Stained Glass Window\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk/index.php/legends/johnny-gregory|title=A PORTRAIT OF JOHNNY GREGORY|last=JOHNSON|first=Bill|date=27 May 2004|website=www.robertfarnonsociety.org.uk|language=en-gb|